BEGIN_PGML_HINT
Two relevant [`x`]-values to use are [`0`] and [`60\text{.}`] (Why?)

END_PGML_HINT

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Time [`x`] is measured in months, and this loan will take [`60`] months to pay off. So we will make a table where the [`x`]-values run from [`0`] to [`60\text{.}`]

>> [@DataTable(
  [
    [[PGML('[`x`]'),
      rowbottom => '3',
      midrule => '1',],
     PGML('[`y=[$f]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`0`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`15`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[1]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`30`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[2]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`45`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[3]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`60`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[4]]`]'),
    ],
  ],
      align => 'cc',
      valign => 'middle',);@]*[@image(insertGraph($image_1), width=>240)@]*  <<

END_PGML_SOLUTION

